{{Infobox language |name = Dewoin |nativename = |pronunciation = |states = [[Liberia]] |speakers = 8,100 |date = 1991 |ref=e18 |familycolor = Niger-Congo |fam2 = [[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3 = [[Kru languages|Kru]] |fam4 = [[Western Kru languages|Western]] |fam5 = Bassa |iso3 = dee |glotto=dewo1238 |glottorefname=Dewoin }}
The '''Dewoin language''', also known as '''De''', '''Dey''', or '''Dei''', is a [[Kru languages|Kru]] language of the [[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] [[language family]]. It is spoken primarily near the coastal areas of [[Montserrado County]] in western [[Liberia]], including the capital [[Monrovia]]. It has a [[lexical similarity]] of 0.72 with the [[Bassa language]].<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=dee | title = Dewoin | accessdate = 2008-03-08 | author = Gordon, Raymond G., Jr. (ed) | year = 2005 | work = [[Ethnologue|Ethnologue: Languages of the World]] | publisher = [[SIL International]] }}</ref>
In 1991, Dewoin was spoken by 8,100 people.<ref> {{cite book | author = Vanderaa, Larry | title = A survey for Christian Reformed World Missions of missions and churches in West Africa | year = 1991 | publisher = Christian Reformed World Missions | location = [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] }}</ref>
