[[File:Gerald Celente RT interview.jpg|thumb|right|[[Gerald Celente]] who coined the term ''presstitute'']]
'''Presstitute''' is a term that applies to [[journalism]] that is misleadingly tailored to fit a particular partisan, financial or business agenda.<ref>{{cite news|last1=David|first1=Supriti|title=#Presstitute: The Online War Against Women With An Opinion SUPRITI DAVID|url=http://www.thecitizen.in/index.php/NewsDetail/index/7/10942/Presstitute-The-Online-War-Against-Women-With-An-Opinion|publisher=TheCitizen|date=June 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Valderama|first1=Tita|title=Who’s the real “presstitute?”|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/whos-the-real-presstitute/287885/|publisher=[[The Manila Times]]|date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> Coined by [[Gerald Celente]], the word is a [[portmanteau]] of '[[news media|press]]' and '[[prostitute]].'<ref>{{cite news|title=Gerald Celente: Meet the man who coined the term presstitute; VK Singh made it famous|url=http://archive.news18.com/news/bihar/gerald-celente-meet-the-man-who-coined-the-term-presstitute-vk-singh-made-it-famous-714955.html|publisher=[[News18 India]]|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref>

The term created controversy after [[General officer|General]] [[Vijay Kumar Singh]], the Indian [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Union Minister of State for External Affairs]], began referring to the media as “presstitutes” in his [[Twitter|tweets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=General V K Singh presses on presstitute again|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/general-v-k-singh-presses-on-presstitute-again/|publisher=[[Indian Express]]|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Baweja|first1=Harinder|title=‘Presstitutes’ and ‘prostitutes’: The language our netas use|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/analysis/presstitutes-and-prostitutes-the-language-our-netas-use/story-4sotjBK2tLpg3Prf4RKz9O.html|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>

